land, United Kingdom","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","Churchover, Warwickshire, England":"Churchover, Warwickshire, England","Coleshill, Warwickshire, England":"Coleshill, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom","Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, England"},"nl":{"1540–1581":"1540–1581","1550–1594":"1550–1594","1530–1599":"1530–1599","1565–1640":"1565–1640","1575–1603":"1575–1603","1520–1594":"1520–1594","1530–1590":"1530–1590","1594":"1594","1550":"1550","1571":"1571","1581":"1581","1590":"1590","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1599":"1599","1565":"1565","1520":"1520","1575":"1575","1563":"1563","1552":"1552","1640":"1640","1530":"1530","1540":"1540","about 1575":"circa 1575","1549":"1549","1603":"1603","Farrington, Devon, England":"Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Churchover, Warwickshire, England":"Churchover, Warwickshire, England","Coleshill, Warwickshire, England":"Coleshill, Warwickshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, England"},"en":{"1540–1581":"1540–1581","1550–1594":"1550–1594","1530–1599":"1530–1599","1565–1640":"1565–1640","1575–1603":"1575–1603","1520–1594":"1520–1594","1530–1590":"1530–1590","1594":"1594","1550":"1550","1571":"1571","1581":"1581","1590":"1590","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1599":"1599","1565":"1565","1520":"1520","1575":"1575","1563":"1563","1552":"1552","1640":"1640","1530":"1530","1540":"1540","about 1575":"about 1575","1549":"1549","1603":"1603","Farrington, Devon, England":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","Churchover, Warwickshire, England":"Churchover, Warwickshire, England","Coleshill, Warwickshire, England":"Coleshill, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom","Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Lowe","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Low  .","German (<b>Löwe</b>) and Danish (<b>Løwe</b>): from Middle High German <i>lēwe</i>, <i>löuwe</i> ‘lion’, hence a nickname for a brave or regal person. In some cases the surname may have been a topographic or habitational name referring to a house or inn distinguished by the sign of a lion. It is also found in Sweden. Compare   Loewe   1,   Lau  ,   Lave  , and   Lurvey  .","Jewish (Ashkenazic; <b>Löwe</b>): artificial name from German <i>Löwe</i> ‘lion’."],"variants":[{"name":"Lau","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Wai, Wing, Kam, Kwok, Ming, Chi, Yuk, Chun, Kin, Ching, Kwan, Man.","German: nickname for a physically strong person, from Middle High German <i>louwe</i>, <i>lauwe</i> ‘lion’. In some cases the surname may have been a topographic or habitational name referring to a house or inn distinguished by the sign of a lion. Compare   Lowe  .","German: topographic name for someone living in a bush-covered area or clearing, Middle Low German <i>lo</i>, <i>loch</i>, <i>lage</i>, Middle High German <i>lō</i>."]},{"name":"Loew","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Erwin, Eckhard, Fritz, Hans, Heinz, Hermann, Manfred, Raimund.","German (mainly <b>Löw</b>): variant of <b>Löwe</b> ‘lion’ (see   Lowe   2). The surname <i>Loew</i> is also found in France (Alsace and Lorraine). Compare   Low   5."]},{"name":"Lobe","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Alois, Erwin, Horst, Otto, Winfried.","German (<b>Löbe</b>): variant of <b>Löwe</b> ‘lion’ (see   Lowe   2).","German: metonymic occupational name for a tanner, from Middle High German <i>lō</i> ‘tanning bark’."]},{"name":"Loewe","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hans, Armin, Gerhard, Helmuth, Klaus, Kurt.","German (mainly <b>Löwe</b>): see   Lowe   2.","Jewish (Ashkenazic; also <b>Löwe</b>): artificial name from German <i>Löwe</i> ‘lion’. Compare   Lowe   3."]},{"name":"Loewen","meanings":["German (<b>Löwen</b>): variant of <b>Löwe</b> ‘lion’ (see   Lowe   2). Compare   Lowen   2."]},{"name":"Low","meanings":["English and Scottish: topographic name for someone who lived near a tumulus, mound or hill, Middle English <i>lowe</i>, from Old English <i>hlāw</i> (see   Law   2).","Scottish and English: nickname for a short man, from Middle English <i>lah</i>, <i>lowe</i> (Old Norse <i>lágr</i>; the word was adopted first into the northern dialects of Middle English, where Scandinavian influence was strong, and then spread south, with regular alteration of the vowel quality).","English and Scottish (of Norman origin): nickname for a violent or dangerous person, from Anglo-Norman French <i>lou</i>, <i>leu</i> ‘wolf’ (from Latin <i>lupus</i>). Wolves were relatively common in Britain at the time when most surnames were formed, as there still existed large tracts of uncleared forest."]},{"name":"Lurvey","meanings":["Americanized form of German <b>Löwe</b> ‘lion’ (see   Lowe   2).","History: Peter Lurvy, the immigrant ancestor of this family, was in Ipswich, MA, by 1679."]}]},{"name":"Ellen","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Helen  , although now no longer associated with that name. Initial <i>H-</i> tended to be added and dropped rather capriciously, leading to many doublets (  compare for example  Esther   and   Hester  ). It is also sometimes used as a short form of   Eleanor  , to which, however, it is unrelated."],"variants":[{"name":"Eleanor","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":9,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705202,"age":18,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705205,"age":29,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705206,"age":31,"year":"1571","julianDay":2294856,"title":"The Royal Exchange is Organized","description":"The Royal Exchange was organized in January 1571 by Sir Thomas Gresham. Gresham is known as the father of English banking.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Ellen Lowe was born in 1540, in Warwickshire, England, her father, Francis Lowe, was 20 and her mother, Thomasine Farrington, was 10. She married Humphrey Dixwell in 1563, in Coleshill, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 daughters. She died in 1581, in Shropshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 41."},"et":{"1540–1581":"1540–1581","1550–1594":"1550–1594","1530–1599"